{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Qjdce9eR25RtqC7Xf6pNup","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<web-app xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n     3→  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"4.0\"\n     4→  xsi:schemaLocation=\"https://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee https://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/web-app_4_0.xsd\">\n     5→  <!-- Overriding system level defaults is a decent usage of XML. -->\n     6→  <context-param>\n     7→    <param-name>javax.faces.PROJECT_STAGE</param-name>\n     8→    <param-value>Development</param-value>\n     9→  </context-param>\n    10→  <context-param>\n    11→    <param-name>javax.faces.CLIENT_WINDOW_MODE</param-name>\n    12→    <param-value>url</param-value>\n    13→  </context-param>\n    14→  <context-param>\n    15→    <param-name>primefaces.THEME</param-name>\n    16→    <param-value>saga</param-value>\n    17→  </context-param>\n    18→  <context-param>\n    19→    <param-name>primefaces.FONT_AWESOME</param-name>\n    20→    <param-value>true</param-value>\n    21→  </context-param>\n    22→  <context-param>\n    23→    <param-name>primefaces.MOVE_SCRIPTS_TO_BOTTOM</param-name>\n    24→    <param-value>true</param-value>\n    25→  </context-param>\n    26→  <mime-mapping>\n    27→    <extension>ttf</extension>\n    28→    <mime-type>application/font-sfnt</mime-type>\n    29→  </mime-mapping>\n    30→  <mime-mapping>\n    31→    <extension>woff</extension>\n    32→    <mime-type>application/font-woff</mime-type>\n    33→  </mime-mapping>\n    34→  <mime-mapping>\n    35→    <extension>woff2</extension>\n    36→    <mime-type>application/font-woff2</mime-type>\n    37→  </mime-mapping>\n    38→  <mime-mapping>\n    39→    <extension>eot</extension>\n    40→    <mime-type>application/vnd.ms-fontobject</mime-type>\n    41→  </mime-mapping>\n    42→  <servlet>\n    43→    <servlet-name>Faces Servlet</servlet-name>\n    44→    <servlet-class>javax.faces.webapp.FacesServlet</servlet-class>\n    45→    <load-on-startup>1</load-on-startup>\n    46→  </servlet>\n    47→  <servlet-mapping>\n    48→    <servlet-name>Faces Servlet</servlet-name>\n    49→    <url-pattern>*.xhtml</url-pattern>\n    50→  </servlet-mapping>\n    51→  <welcome-file-list>\n    52→    <welcome-file>index.xhtml</welcome-file>\n    53→    <welcome-file>index.html</welcome-file>\n    54→  </welcome-file-list>\n    55→  <!-- Application resource dependencies like JMS queues and data sources are still\n    56→    good candidates for XML, as is application configuration. -->\n    57→  <env-entry>\n    58→    <env-entry-name>java:app/configuration/GraphTraversalUrl</env-entry-name>\n    59→    <env-entry-type>java.lang.String</env-entry-type>\n    60→    <env-entry-value>${webapp.graphTraversalUrl}</env-entry-value>\n    61→  </env-entry>\n    62→  <!-- Defining these at the application server level instead of here can be more\n    63→    operations friendly and help make deployment even faster. -->\n    64→  <data-source>\n    65→    <name>java:app/jdbc/CargoTrackerDatabase</name>\n    66→    <class-name>${db.driverClass}</class-name>\n    67→    <url>${db.jdbcUrl}</url>\n    68→    <user>${db.user}</user>\n    69→    <password>${db.password}</password>\n    70→    <max-pool-size>32</max-pool-size>\n    71→    <min-pool-size>2</min-pool-size>\n    72→  </data-source>\n    73→  <jms-destination>\n    74→    <name>java:app/jms/CargoHandledQueue</name>\n    75→    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    76→    <destination-name>CargoHandledQueue</destination-name>\n    77→  </jms-destination>\n    78→  <jms-destination>\n    79→    <name>java:app/jms/MisdirectedCargoQueue</name>\n    80→    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    81→    <destination-name>MisdirectedCargoQueue</destination-name>\n    82→  </jms-destination>\n    83→  <jms-destination>\n    84→    <name>java:app/jms/DeliveredCargoQueue</name>\n    85→    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    86→    <destination-name>DeliveredCargoQueue</destination-name>\n    87→  </jms-destination>\n    88→  <jms-destination>\n    89→    <name>java:app/jms/RejectedRegistrationAttemptsQueue</name>\n    90→    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    91→    <destination-name>RejectedRegistrationAttemptsQueue</destination-name>\n    92→  </jms-destination>\n    93→  <jms-destination>\n    94→    <name>java:app/jms/HandlingEventRegistrationAttemptQueue</name>\n    95→    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    96→    <destination-name>HandlingEventRegistrationAttemptQueue</destination-name>\n    97→  </jms-destination>\n    98→</web-app>\n    99→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"e9a47756-78f8-4c3a-966f-2d9c72b2560c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RaapoiwAcsrHtUugXtWBE6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<beans version=\"2.0\" xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n     3→  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n     4→  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/beans_2_0.xsd\"\n     5→  bean-discovery-mode=\"all\">\n     6→</beans>\n     7→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"926cd1e0-16f4-4afc-9987-a73165db55ed"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01TamW9mjYLrh8YmFsmPTEbp","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<faces-config xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n     3→  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"2.3\"\n     4→  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/web-facesconfig_2_3.xsd\">\n     5→  <application>\n     6→    <action-listener>org.primefaces.application.DialogActionListener</action-listener>\n     7→    <navigation-handler>org.primefaces.application.DialogNavigationHandler</navigation-handler>\n     8→    <view-handler>org.primefaces.application.DialogViewHandler</view-handler>\n     9→  </application>\n    10→</faces-config>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"85aa19a4-22dd-4708-b7bf-1ee2ab0e90a5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01GoiESuMnuvQjSVxrk7hB1T","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<!DOCTYPE glassfish-web-app PUBLIC \"-//GlassFish.org//DTD GlassFish Application Server 3.1 Servlet 3.0//EN\" \"http://glassfish.org/dtds/glassfish-web-app_3_0-1.dtd\">\n     3→<glassfish-web-app>\n     4→  <context-root>/cargo-tracker</context-root>\n     5→  <class-loader delegate=\"true\" />\n     6→  <jsp-config>\n     7→    <property name=\"keepgenerated\" value=\"true\" />\n     8→  </jsp-config>\n     9→  <parameter-encoding default-charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n    10→</glassfish-web-app>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"cb1ae40e-c6d3-4262-8cd1-79e38b59730e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01F2g8SgwhzJYqXYMD9PuWGq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<persistence xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence\"\n     3→  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"2.1\"\n     4→  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence/persistence_2_1.xsd\">\n     5→  <persistence-unit name=\"CargoTrackerUnit\">\n     6→    <jta-data-source>java:app/jdbc/CargoTrackerDatabase</jta-data-source>\n     7→    <shared-cache-mode>ALL</shared-cache-mode>\n     8→    <properties>\n     9→      <!-- The default behavior is not generating a schema. Schema generation is \n    10→        good for demos, RAD, development, etc but likely not a good idea for production. -->\n    11→      <property\n    12→        name=\"javax.persistence.schema-generation.database.action\"\n    13→        value=\"create\" />\n    14→      <!-- This will fail if it's not invoked on a blank database - this is fine. \n    15→        What this does is insert a single record that the application settings check can \n    16→        place a pessimistic lock on. -->\n    17→      <property name=\"javax.persistence.sql-load-script-source\"\n    18→        value=\"META-INF/initital-data.sql\" />\n    19→      <!-- The default log level of info is best for production, want to see verbose \n    20→        output for development. -->\n    21→      <property name=\"eclipselink.logging.level\" value=\"FINEST\" />\n    22→    </properties>\n    23→  </persistence-unit>\n    24→</persistence>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"8d5a2600-e027-45bf-9733-e3e2541f6d48"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01REFmxdShyvMLhdgQAPuNYR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<job xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\" id=\"EventFilesProcessorJob\"\n     3→  version=\"1.0\">\n     4→  <properties>\n     5→    <property name=\"upload_directory\" value=\"/tmp/uploads\" />\n     6→    <property name=\"archive_directory\" value=\"/tmp/archive\" />\n     7→    <property name=\"failed_directory\" value=\"/tmp/failed\" />\n     8→  </properties>\n     9→  <listeners>\n    10→    <listener ref=\"FileProcessorJobListener\" />\n    11→  </listeners>\n    12→  <step id=\"ProcessEventFiles\">\n    13→    <listeners>\n    14→      <listener ref=\"LineParseExceptionListener\" />\n    15→    </listeners>\n    16→    <chunk item-count=\"12\">\n    17→      <reader ref=\"EventItemReader\" />\n    18→      <writer ref=\"EventItemWriter\" />\n    19→      <skippable-exception-classes>\n    20→        <include\n    21→          class=\"org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.handling.file.EventLineParseException\" />\n    22→      </skippable-exception-classes>\n    23→    </chunk>\n    24→  </step>\n    25→</job>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Sa4LJ8bVwnA1GZ39eebxRZ","session_id":"18f7ec53-4184-4cad-96bc-6843d85e3d1e","uuid":"cc4ec73b-6b9c-415b-89ca-43647363d696"}
